Evaluating Model Performance

Measuring performance for regression

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE) is the sum of the absolute differences between predictions and actual values;

\[ \text{MAE} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 1}^N |y_i - \hat{y_i}| \]

  • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) is square root of the variance of the residuals;

\[ \text{MSE} = \sum_{i = 1}^N (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2 \]

  • Taking the square root of the MSE converts the units back to the original units;

  • \(R^2\) (R-Squared) metric provides an indication of the goodness of fit;

\[ R^2 = 1 - \frac{\sum_{i = 1}^N (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2}{\sum_{i = 1}^N (y_i - \overline{y_i})^2} \]

  • This is a value between \(0\) and \(1\).

Measuring performance for classification

  • Until now, we have only examined classification predictions using actual and predicted classes;

  • Most of the models can supply another piece of information: the probability;

  • It is ideal to fit a model:
    • Extremely confident when making correct predictions;
    • Timid in the face of doubt.

Confusion Matrix

  • CM is a performance measurement for machine learning classification problems;

  • It is a table with 4 different combinations of predicted and actual values;

  • It is extremely useful for measuring Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1-score.

Confusion Matrix

Accuracy

  • Accuracy is given by

\[ \text{Acc} = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + FP + FN + TN} \]

Recall

  • Recall (Sensitivity): out of all the actual positive classes, how much we predicted correctly;

\[ \text{Recall} = \frac{TP}{TP + FN} \]

Precision

  • Precision: out of all the predicted positive classes, how much we predicted correctly;

\[ \text{Precision} = \frac{TP}{TP + FP} \]

Performance for Skewed Classes

  • It is sometimes difficult to tell whether a reduction in error is an improvement of the algorithm;

  • For instance: suppose we are predicting a cancer diagnoses where \(0.5\%\) of the examples have cancer;

  • We find our learning algorithm has a \(1\%\) error. Sounds very good, right?!

  • Suppose an algorithm simply classify every single example as a 0. Which is the error?

  • This usually happens with skewed classes;

  • Using accuracy as a performance metric could be misleading;

  • For these cases, better use recall and precision;

Trade off between Recall and Precision

  • Default behavior of every algorithm is to assign an obs to a class w-ith the greatest probability;

  • In the case of \(K\) classes, this rule is greater than \(1/K\);

  • Again, consider the case where we are predicting a cancer diagnoses where 0.5% of the examples have cancer;

  • We change our threshold and classify as positive if \(P(x) \gt 0.7\);

\[ \text{Recall} \downarrow \quad \text{Precision} \uparrow \]

  • Now, lets pretend our threshold moved to something as \(P(x) \gt 0.3\); \[ \text{Recall} \uparrow \quad \text{Precision} \downarrow \]

  • That is, there is a trade-off between Recall and Precision;

  • But, we want both to be high! What now?

F1 Score

  • One way we can circumvent this issue is to combine Recall and Precision into a single metric;

  • Average? \[ \frac{\text{Recall} + \text{Precision}}{2} \]

  • I dont think so!!

  • A better way is to compute the F Score (or F1 score):

\[ F1 = \frac{2^*\text{Recall}^*\text{Precision}}{\text{Recall} + \text{Precision}} \]

  • In order for the F Score to be large, both Precision and Recall must be large;

Kappa

  • Kappa statistics adjust accuracy by account for the possibility of a correct prediction by chance;

  • This is especially important for datasets with severe class imbalance;

  • The Kappa will only reward the algorithm if it correct more often that this simplistic strategy;

  • Kappa values range from \(0\) to \(1\);

  • Kappa are calculated as

\[ \kappa = \frac{P(a) - P(e)}{1 - P(e)} \] where:

  • \(P(a)\) refers to the proportion of actual agreement (accuracy);
  • \(P(e)\) refers to the expected agreement between the classifier and the true values, under the assumption chosen at random;

Kappa

\[ P(a) = \frac{50+100}{50 + 10 + 5 + 100} = 0.909 \]

\[ P(e) = \frac{55}{165}*\frac{60}{165} + \frac{110}{165}*\frac{105}{165} = 0.545 \] \[ \kappa = \frac{0.909 - 0.545}{1 - 0.545} = 0.8 \]

AUC - ROC curve

  • Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) is the most commonly used way to visualize the performance of a binary classifier;

  • AUC is (arguably) the best way to summarize its performance in a single number.

  • ROC curve is used to examine the trade-off of true and false positives;

  • It tells how much model is capable of distinguishing between classes;

  • Higher the AUC, better the model is at predicting 0s as 0s and 1s as 1s;

LogLoss

  • Logarithm Loss is a classification loss function commonly used as evaluation metric;

  • LogLoss quantifies the accuracy of a classifier by highly penalising false classifications;

  • In order to calculate LogLoss the classifier must assign a probability to each class;

  • Minimising the LogLoss is equivalent to maximising the accuracy of the classifier;

  • Mathematically LogLoss is defined as

\[ -\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N \sum_{k = 1}^K y_{ik} \log p_{ik} \] where:

  • \(N\) is the number of samples;
  • \(K\) is the number of classes;
  • \(y_{ik}\) is a binary indicator of wheter \(y_{ik}\) is correctly classified;
  • \(p_{ik}\) is the model probability.

LogLoss

Estimating Future Performance

Resampling Methods

  • Resampling methods are indispensable tool;

  • They involve repeatedly drawing sample from a training set and refitting a model on each sample;

  • Resampling methods can be computationall expensive;

  • We will discuss the most commonly used resampling approaches:

    • Holdout method;
    • Cross-validation method;

  • All of these techniques can be used to estimate the test error;

Holdout Method

  • In general, (almost) do not care about training performance;

  • Performance on unseen data;

  • Problem: unseen data is unseen;

  • The most simple approach to estimate future performance: holdout method;

  • Involves randomly dividing the available set into two parts:

    1. training set;
    2. validation set;

  • The model is fit on training set and the prediction is made on validation set;

  • The resulting validation performance provides an estimate of future performance;

Holdout Method

  • Holdout method is conceptually simple;

  • Easy to implement;

  • However, it has two potential drawbacks:

    1. The validation estimate of the test error can be highly variable;
    2. The validation estimate may tend to overestimate the future performance;

Cross Validation Method

  • Cross-validation is another resampling method used to estimate the future performance;

  • It involves splitting the dataset into \(K\) different folders;

  • Hold the folder \(k\) as a validation set;

  • Use \(K-1\) folders as training set to fit the model;

  • Make prediction on the \(k\) folder;

  • Repeat the process for each \(k\), where \(k = 1, 2, ..., K\);

  • In the end, we will have a set of \(K\) performance;

Cross Validation Method

  • The final estimate for future performance will be the average of \(K\) metrics;

  • CV method has demonstrated exccelent estimates for future performance;

  • But not only to estimate future performance can CV be used;

  • Also, choose tunning parameters;

Algorithm Tunning Parameter
KNN Number of neighbors (\(K\))
Ridge \(\lambda_1\)
LASSO \(\lambda_2\)
Elastic Net \(\lambda_1\), \(\lambda_2\)
Random Forest Number of features (\(m) Boosting | learning rate (\)\(), number of rounds (\)B$)
Neural Network Number of layers, number of hidden units

Economics Applications

Source of Economic Growth: Barro and Lee (1994) revisited

  • Growth rates vary enormously across countries over long periods of time;

  • For 116 countries from 1965 to 1985;

  • The lowest quintile had an average growth rate of real per capita GDP of \(-1.3\%\);

  • The highest quintile had an average of \(4.8\%\);

  • The key challenge for economists is to understand why growth outcomes differ so much;

  • build on previous cross-country empirical analyses to isolate major determinants of growth rates;

Source of Economic Growth: Barro and Lee (1994) revisited

  • They describe in terms of five key determinants of growth:
  1. Conditional convergence effect (real per-capita GDP relative to its initial level of human capital);
  2. high ratio of investment to GDP;
  3. Large government (ratio of government consumption to GDP);
  4. Government-induced distortions of markets (black-market premium on foreign exchange);
  5. Political instability (propensity toward revolutions).

  • What if we had a method in which we extract what is important in a data-driven way?

Can Machine Learning Help Predict the Outcome of Asylum Adjudications?

Chen and Eagel, Computational Analysis of Law, Forthcoming

  • They analyzed almost \(500K\) asylum hearings from 336 different hearing locations;

  • Rendered by 441 unique judges over a thirty-two year period from 1981-2013;

  • The problem of asylum adjudication is a binary classification problem;

  • Using Random Forest, we predict twenty-seven years of refugee decisions.

  • Using only data available up to the decision date, they correctly classifies \(82\%\);

Can Machine Learning Help Predict the Outcome of Asylum Adjudications?

Chen and Eagel, Computational Analysis of Law, Forthcoming

  • Results:
    • Decision makers exhibit a fair degree of autocorrelation in their rulings;
    • Extraneous factors such as, news and the local weather may be impacting the fate of an asylum seeker;
    • Surprisingly, granting asylum is predominantly driven by trend features and judicial characteristics- features;
    • one third-driven by case information, news events, and court information;

Can Machine Learning Help Predict the Outcome of Asylum Adjudications?

Chen and Eagel, Computational Analysis of Law, Forthcoming

  • An individual may apply for refugee status in the United States either affirmatively or defensively.

  • Dataset contained approximately five hundred thousand cases and 137 features.

  • classified each feature into one of six buckets:

  1. case information (number of family members, date of hearing, and whether the application was affirmative or defensive);
  2. judge information (law school graduation year, gender, President, military);
  3. court information (number of hearings per day, historical factors);
  4. trend (historical factors);
  5. weather (NOAA);
  6. news (media coverage may weigh on a justices consciousness when ruling);

Estimating the Effect of Institutions on Output

Acemoglu at al (2001) revisited

  • Consider the estimation of the effect of institutions on aggregate output following the work of Acemoglu et al.(2001);

  • E mploy an IV method and argue for the use of mortality rates for early European settlers as an IV for Institution;

  • A potential candidate for such factor is geography. Hence, the authors control for the distance from the equator (latitude).

  • Formally, their IV model can be represented as

\[ Y_t = \mu + \alpha R_t + X'_t \beta + \epsilon_t \\ R_t = \zeta + \gamma \log(M_t) + X'\eta + \upsilon_t\\ \]

  • where
    • Y is a measure of countrys output;
    • R is a measure of institution,
    • M is the mortality rate for early settlers, and
    • X is the matrix with geography control variable.
  • The data set contain information on 64 countries;
  • The geography information is composed by: latitude and dummies for continents;

  • It is implicitly assumed that the confounding effect of geography is properly captured by a linear term in latitude;
  • The use of high-dimensional method could allow us to alleviate this assumption.
  • The set of variables considered are the same as in Acemoglu et al.(2001);
  • With additional non-linear terms for latitude:
    • Dummies for Africa, Asia, North America and South America;
    • Cubic-spline in latitude with three knots;
  • To make use of this enhanced X, note that the model is equivalent to the three-system:

\[ Y_t = \mu + \alpha R + X'\beta + \epsilon \\ R_t = \pi_1 log(M) + X'\Pi_2 + v_t \\ log(M_t) = X'_t\gamma + u_t \]

  • which yields three reduced form equations:

\[ Y_t = X'\tilde{\beta} + \tilde{\epsilon}_t \\ R_t = X'_t\tilde{\Pi}_2 + \tilde{u}_t \\ log(M_t) = X'_t{\gamma} + u_i \]

  • Thus, select a set of control features by carrying out variable selection;

  • After selecting the columns of X, valid estimation and inference can be estimated using IV;
